## Strategy playbook

The strategy design below is grounded in a simple research view of Bitcoin microstructure. Trend-following can work in Bitcoin, especially trading-range breakout logic; intraday mean reversion also exists, especially after outsized moves; and cost-aware studies show technical trading can remain useful out-of-sample but gets more fragile as turnover rises. That is why these models are regime-specific and explicitly reject trades whenever the spread or stop geometry is unfavourable. All four are EA-friendly because they use native MT5 indicators, or in the case of the Donchian channel, a rolling highest-high/lowest-low built from standard time-series functions. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn12search1Ņłéturn14view2Ņłéturn26view0Ņłéturn6search0Ņłéturn6search1Ņłéturn6search2Ņłéturn8search0Ņłéturn8search1Ņłéturn8search2Ņłéturn8search3Ņłéturn25search0Ņłéturn25search1Ņłü

![Illustrative BTC scalping indicator setup mockup](sandbox:/mnt/data/btc_scalping_indicator_mockup.png)

This synthetic mock-up is not live BTC data. It is included purely to show how the four signal families appear on-chart in an MT5-style setup.

**EMA pullback continuation**

This is the most balanced starting strategy. It assumes BTC is already trending and waits for a shallow pullback before rejoining the move. Long regime filter: on **M5**, `EMA50 > EMA200`, the last completed M5 close is above EMA50, and EMA50 has a positive slope over the last three completed M5 bars. Long trigger: on **M1**, at least one of the last three completed lows touched or dipped below EMA21; then the latest completed M1 bar has `EMA9 > EMA21`, `RSI14` crossing **up through 52** from below, and a close above the previous barŌĆÖs high. Shorts use the exact mirror image. The reliance on MA, RSI and ATR is fully native to MT5, while the cost-aware, bar-close approach is consistent with the evidence that technical-rule edge in Bitcoin is real but more fragile at the highest turnover levels. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn6search0Ņłéturn6search1Ņłéturn6search2Ņłéturn26view0Ņłü

Use a stop that is the **wider** of the pullback swing and `0.9 ├Ś ATR14(M1)`, then add a spread buffer. In notation:  
`SL distance = max(entry - pullback_swing_low + spread, 0.9 ├Ś ATR14)`.  
Reject the trade if the resulting stop is below **0.12%** or above **0.20%** of entry. Set TP at **1.5R**. At BTC 61,657.4 and `SYMBOL_POINT = 0.01`, that means a practical SL band of about **7,399 to 12,331 points** and a TP band of roughly **11,098 to 18,497 points**, corresponding to around **0.12% to 0.20% SL** and **0.18% to 0.30% TP**. Risk **0.35% to 0.60%** of equity per trade. Expected win-rate range: **44% to 52%**. Spread sensitivity is **moderate**; I would skip the trade if spread is above about **12% of the planned stop distance**. As an optional regime filter, this model is usually cleaner during the brokerŌĆÖs most liquid Europe/US window, which fits the intraday evidence that Bitcoin activity and volatility tend to peak during US trading hours. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn22calculator2Ņłéturn23calculator0Ņłéturn23calculator1Ņłéturn24calculator0Ņłéturn28search1Ņłéturn14view0Ņłü

```mql5
// Strategy A: EMA pullback continuation
if (NewClosedBar(PERIOD_M1))
{
    bool trendLong =
        ema50_m5[1] > ema200_m5[1] &&
        close_m5[1] > ema50_m5[1] &&
        ema50_m5[1] > ema50_m5[4];

    bool pullbackTouched =
        (low_m1[1] <= ema21_m1[1]) ||
        (low_m1[2] <= ema21_m1[2]) ||
        (low_m1[3] <= ema21_m1[3]);

    bool triggerLong =
        ema9_m1[1] > ema21_m1[1] &&
        rsi14_m1[2] < 52 && rsi14_m1[1] >= 52 &&
        close_m1[1] > high_m1[2];

    if (trendLong && pullbackTouched && triggerLong)
    {
        double entry = SymbolInfoDouble(_Symbol, SYMBOL_ASK);
        double spread = (double)SymbolInfoInteger(_Symbol, SYMBOL_SPREAD) * _Point;
        double swingLow = MathMin(low_m1[1], MathMin(low_m1[2], low_m1[3]));
        double slDist = MathMax((entry - swingLow) + spread, 0.9 * atr14_m1[1]);

        if (slDist >= 0.0012 * entry &&
            slDist <= 0.0020 * entry &&
            SymbolInfoInteger(_Symbol, SYMBOL_SPREAD) <= 0.12 * (slDist / _Point))
        {
            double sl = entry - slDist;
            double tp = entry + 1.5 * slDist;
            double lots = SizeByRisk(entry, sl, 0.005); // 0.5% example
            SendBuy(lots, sl, tp);
        }
    }
}
```

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[New closed M1 bar] --> B{M5 EMA50 > EMA200 and close > EMA50?}
    B -- No --> Z[No trade]
    B -- Yes --> C{Touched EMA21 in last 3 M1 bars?}
    C -- No --> Z
    C -- Yes --> D{EMA9 > EMA21 and RSI14 cross above 52 and close > prev high?}
    D -- No --> Z
    D -- Yes --> E[Compute SL from swing or 0.9 ATR]
    E --> F{Spread <= 12% of SL and SL within 0.12%-0.20%?}
    F -- No --> Z
    F -- Yes --> G[Place long with TP = 1.5R]
```

**Bollinger range fade**

This is the highest win-rate model in the set, but also the most spread-sensitive. It is only for quiet, range-like conditions. Range filter: on **M5**, `ADX14 < 18` and the 50-EMA is flat enough that `abs(EMA50[1] - EMA50[6]) / Close[1] < 0.05%`. Long trigger: on **M1**, the bar before the trigger closes below the lower Bollinger Band (`Bands 20, 2.0`) and `RSI2 < 8`; then the latest completed bar closes **back inside** the band, closes bullish, and RSI2 turns higher versus the previous bar. Shorts are the mirror image with `RSI2 > 92` and a close back inside the upper band. The logic is directly aligned with the intraday evidence that larger directional moves in Bitcoin tend to be followed by stronger reversals on some horizons. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn8search0Ņłéturn6search2Ņłéturn6search1Ņłéturn8search1Ņłéturn14view2Ņłü

Set the stop using the **widest** of four guards: the signal extreme, `0.6 ├Ś ATR14(M1)`, `1.5 ├Ś spread`, and an absolute floor of **0.08%** of entry. Reject the trade if the resulting stop exceeds **0.14%** of entry. Exit fully at the **Bollinger midline**, but only take the trade if the distance from entry to the midline is between **0.8R and 1.3R**. That produces a practical stop band of roughly **4,933 to 8,632 points** and a typical TP band around **4,933 to 9,865 points** under the illustrative point assumption, equivalent to around **0.08% to 0.14% SL** and often **0.08% to 0.16% TP**. Risk **0.25% to 0.40%** of equity. Expected win-rate range: **58% to 68%**. Spread/slippage sensitivity is **high**; I would generally reject the setup if spread exceeds **15% of the planned stop** or if the brokerŌĆÖs stop level forces an unattractive RR. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn22calculator0Ņłéturn24calculator2Ņłéturn30calculator0Ņłéturn28search1Ņłéturn21search1Ņłéturn21search5Ņłü

```mql5
// Strategy B: Bollinger range fade
if (NewClosedBar(PERIOD_M1))
{
    bool rangeMarket =
        adx14_m5[1] < 18 &&
        MathAbs(ema50_m5[1] - ema50_m5[6]) / close_m5[1] < 0.0005;

    bool oversoldSetup =
        close_m1[2] < bbLower_m1[2] &&
        rsi2_m1[2] < 8;

    bool reEntryLong =
        close_m1[1] > bbLower_m1[1] &&
        close_m1[1] > open_m1[1] &&
        rsi2_m1[1] > rsi2_m1[2];

    if (rangeMarket && oversoldSetup && reEntryLong)
    {
        double entry = SymbolInfoDouble(_Symbol, SYMBOL_ASK);
        double spread = (double)SymbolInfoInteger(_Symbol, SYMBOL_SPREAD) * _Point;
        double slDist = MathMax((entry - low_m1[1]) + spread,
                         MathMax(0.6 * atr14_m1[1],
                         MathMax(1.5 * spread, 0.0008 * entry)));
        double tp = bbMid_m1[1];

        if (slDist <= 0.0014 * entry &&
            (tp - entry) >= 0.8 * slDist &&
            (tp - entry) <= 1.3 * slDist)
        {
            double sl = entry - slDist;
            double lots = SizeByRisk(entry, sl, 0.003); // 0.3% example
            SendBuy(lots, sl, tp);
        }
    }
}
```

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[New closed M1 bar] --> B{M5 ADX < 18 and EMA50 flat?}
    B -- No --> Z[No trade]
    B -- Yes --> C{Previous M1 close outside lower band and RSI2 < 8?}
    C -- No --> Z
    C -- Yes --> D{Latest M1 close back inside band and bullish?}
    D -- No --> Z
    D -- Yes --> E[Compute SL from extreme, ATR, spread floor]
    E --> F{Mid-band target gives 0.8R to 1.3R?}
    F -- No --> Z
    F -- Yes --> G[Place long, TP = Bollinger midline]
```

**Donchian volatility breakout**

This is the most aggressive strategy and the most exposed to adverse slippage, so it should only be live in expansion regimes. Regime filter: on **M5**, `ADX14 > 22` and rising over the last three completed bars. Volatility trigger: on **M1**, `ATR14 > 1.10 ├Ś SMA20(ATR14)`. Breakout trigger: the latest completed M1 close exceeds the **highest high of the prior 20 completed M1 bars** by at least `0.05 ├Ś ATR14`, and `MACD histogram > 0`. Shorts use the rolling lowest low and a negative histogram. This is essentially a Donchian or trading-range breakout implementation, which has good support in the Bitcoin literature relative to many other trend rules. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn8search1Ņłéturn8search2Ņłéturn6search1Ņłéturn25search0Ņłéturn25search1Ņłéturn12search1Ņłü

Set the stop as the wider of the breakout-bar extreme and `1.0 ├Ś ATR14(M1)`, then reject the trade if the stop is below **0.18%** or above **0.30%** of entry. The default TP is **1.8R**, with a break-even stop move after **+1R**. Under the illustrative point assumption that translates to about **11,098 to 18,497 points of SL** and roughly **19,730 to 33,295 points of TP**, or about **0.18% to 0.30% SL** and **0.32% to 0.54% TP**. Risk **0.35% to 0.60%** of equity. Expected win-rate range: **34% to 45%**. Spread sensitivity is only **moderate**, but **slippage sensitivity is high** because bad fills happen precisely when the breakout is most explosive. If your broker offers DOM data, this is the strategy that benefits most from a pre-trade liquidity check. It also benefits from being limited to the brokerŌĆÖs most liquid Europe/US window, which is consistent with the academic evidence on higher activity and lower spreads during US hours. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn23calculator0Ņłéturn24calculator0Ņłéturn30calculator3Ņłéturn31calculator2Ņłéturn9search1Ņłéturn9search5Ņłéturn14view0Ņłü

```mql5
// Strategy C: Donchian volatility breakout
if (NewClosedBar(PERIOD_M1))
{
    bool trendExpansion =
        adx14_m5[1] > 22 &&
        adx14_m5[1] > adx14_m5[2] &&
        adx14_m5[2] > adx14_m5[3] &&
        atr14_m1[1] > 1.10 * atr14_sma20_m1[1];

    int hhIdx = iHighest(_Symbol, PERIOD_M1, MODE_HIGH, 20, 2);
    double breakoutHigh = iHigh(_Symbol, PERIOD_M1, hhIdx);

    bool breakoutLong =
        close_m1[1] > breakoutHigh + 0.05 * atr14_m1[1] &&
        macdHist_m1[1] > 0;

    if (trendExpansion && breakoutLong)
    {
        double entry = SymbolInfoDouble(_Symbol, SYMBOL_ASK);
        double spread = (double)SymbolInfoInteger(_Symbol, SYMBOL_SPREAD) * _Point;
        double slDist = MathMax((entry - low_m1[1]) + spread, 1.0 * atr14_m1[1]);

        if (slDist >= 0.0018 * entry && slDist <= 0.0030 * entry)
        {
            double sl = entry - slDist;
            double tp = entry + 1.8 * slDist;
            double lots = SizeByRisk(entry, sl, 0.0045); // 0.45% example
            SendBuy(lots, sl, tp);
        }
    }
}
```

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[New closed M1 bar] --> B{M5 ADX > 22 and rising?}
    B -- No --> Z[No trade]
    B -- Yes --> C{M1 ATR > 1.10 x ATR SMA20?}
    C -- No --> Z
    C -- Yes --> D{Close breaks 20-bar high by 0.05 ATR and MACD hist > 0?}
    D -- No --> Z
    D -- Yes --> E[Compute SL from breakout bar low or 1.0 ATR]
    E --> F{SL within 0.18%-0.30% and spread acceptable?}
    F -- No --> Z
    F -- Yes --> G[Place long, TP = 1.8R]
```

**MACD-Stochastic re-entry**

This is the best ŌĆ£secondary continuationŌĆØ strategy when the market is trending but not clean enough for pure breakout logic. Long regime filter: on **M15**, the latest close is above EMA200, `EMA50 > EMA200`, and EMA200 slope is positive. Long trigger: on **M3**, the latest completed bar closes above EMA20, `MACD histogram` flips from negative to positive, the MACD main line is still below zero or just around the zero-line, `Stochastic 5,3,3` has `%K` crossing above `%D` from below **25**, and the signal candle closes in the top 40% of its range. Shorts are mirrored. This uses only standard MT5 indicators and leans on the broad result that moving average, filter and related continuation rules can add value in Bitcoin, though their effectiveness varies by period and cost environment. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn8search2Ņłéturn8search3Ņłéturn6search1Ņłéturn6search0Ņłéturn26view0Ņłü

Use the wider of the local re-entry swing and `0.75 ├Ś ATR14(M3)` as the stop, but reject the trade if that stop is below **0.14%** or above **0.24%** of entry. Target **1.5R** by default, but if the nearest **M15 swing high** offers less than **1.2R**, skip the trade; if it offers between **1.2R and 1.6R**, use that structural target instead of a pure multiple. Under the same illustrative point assumption, the stop band is about **8,632 to 14,798 points**, and the practical TP band is around **12,948 to 23,430 points**, matching roughly **0.14% to 0.24% SL** and **0.21% to 0.38% TP**. Risk **0.30% to 0.50%** of equity. Expected win-rate range: **46% to 55%**. Spread sensitivity is **moderate**, and slippage sensitivity is lower than the breakout model because the entry is on a pullback resumption rather than a fresh range expansion. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn24calculator2Ņłéturn23calculator3Ņłéturn30calculator2Ņłéturn31calculator1Ņłéturn28search1Ņłü

```mql5
// Strategy D: MACD-Stochastic re-entry
if (NewClosedBar(PERIOD_M3))
{
    bool trendLong =
        close_m15[1] > ema200_m15[1] &&
        ema50_m15[1] > ema200_m15[1] &&
        ema200_m15[1] > ema200_m15[4];

    bool triggerLong =
        close_m3[1] > ema20_m3[1] &&
        macdHist_m3[2] <= 0 && macdHist_m3[1] > 0 &&
        stochK_m3[2] <= stochD_m3[2] &&
        stochK_m3[1] > stochD_m3[1] &&
        stochK_m3[1] < 25 &&
        (close_m3[1] - low_m3[1]) / MathMax(high_m3[1] - low_m3[1], _Point) >= 0.60;

    if (trendLong && triggerLong)
    {
        double entry = SymbolInfoDouble(_Symbol, SYMBOL_ASK);
        double spread = (double)SymbolInfoInteger(_Symbol, SYMBOL_SPREAD) * _Point;
        double swingLow = MathMin(low_m3[1], low_m3[2]);
        double slDist = MathMax((entry - swingLow) + spread, 0.75 * atr14_m3[1]);

        if (slDist >= 0.0014 * entry && slDist <= 0.0024 * entry)
        {
            double structuralTarget = NearestM15Resistance(entry);
            if ((structuralTarget - entry) >= 1.2 * slDist)
            {
                double sl = entry - slDist;
                double tp = MathMin(entry + 1.5 * slDist, structuralTarget);
                double lots = SizeByRisk(entry, sl, 0.004); // 0.4% example
                SendBuy(lots, sl, tp);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[New closed M3 bar] --> B{M15 close > EMA200 and EMA50 > EMA200?}
    B -- No --> Z[No trade]
    B -- Yes --> C{M3 close > EMA20?}
    C -- No --> Z
    C -- Yes --> D{MACD hist flips positive and Stoch K crosses above D below 25?}
    D -- No --> Z
    D -- Yes --> E[Compute SL from swing or 0.75 ATR]
    E --> F{Nearest M15 resistance >= 1.2R?}
    F -- No --> Z
    F -- Yes --> G[Place long, TP = min 1.5R or M15 resistance]
```

## Automation and optimisation

For MT5 EAs, the cleanest architecture is usually: **signal evaluation on completed bars, execution and management on ticks**. The platformŌĆÖs `OnTick()` event is designed for new-quote handling; bar and tick data are available through the standard series access in MQL5 and through the MetaTrader5 Python package via functions such as `copy_rates_from_pos`, `copy_ticks_range`, `symbol_info_tick`, and `positions_get`. The Python integration also stores bar/tick times in UTC, which matters if you add a session filter or if you evaluate performance by hour-of-day. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn7search1Ņłéturn7search2Ņłéturn9search3Ņłéturn9search2Ņłéturn7search3Ņłéturn7search6Ņłü

For position sizing, avoid hard-coding BTC lot math. MT5 already provides pre-trade valuation tools. In MQL5 you can use `OrderCalcProfit()` and `OrderCalcMargin()`, and in Python their analogues are `order_calc_profit()` and `order_calc_margin()`. That is safer than assuming a universal tick value for every BTC symbol because broker specifications differ. A robust pattern is: calculate the loss for **1.0 lot** between entry and stop, divide your allowed risk cash by that one-lot loss, and then round down to the brokerŌĆÖs volume step. Use `order_check()` before `order_send()` in Python, or the MQL5 equivalents, to catch margin or trade-parameter errors early. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn29search1Ņłéturn29search3Ņłéturn21search6Ņłéturn21search2Ņłéturn9search0Ņłéturn6search3Ņłéturn9search4Ņłü

For cost control, your EA should query **spread**, **minimum stop level**, and if available **DOM depth** before sending an order. MT5 exposes spread in points and the brokerŌĆÖs minimum stop level through symbol information and the standard library; depth-of-market subscriptions are available through `MarketBookAdd()` in MQL5 and `market_book_add()` in Python when the broker supplies book data. If you are on a **netting** account, remember that MT5 permits only one position per symbol, so these strategies should be run through a single BTC portfolio controller rather than four independent EAs fighting one another. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn21search0Ņłéturn21search1Ņłéturn21search5Ņłéturn9search1Ņłéturn9search5Ņłéturn32search0Ņłü

For optimisation, keep the search narrow and interpretable. MT5ŌĆÖs Strategy Tester supports testing and optimisation, and MQL5 also lets you process optimisation results programmatically. I would not optimise raw net profit alone. A more robust objective for BTC scalping is a composite such as **expectancy per trade adjusted for max drawdown, spread deterioration, and slippage penalty**. Then confirm on forward periods or a walk-forward process. The cost-aware Bitcoin literature is very clear that frequency and transaction costs interact strongly, so your optimisation must explicitly include spread/slippage stress rather than assuming ideal fills. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn20search1Ņłéturn20search12Ņłéturn20search2Ņłéturn26view0Ņłü

Useful optimisation bands, without overfitting, are these:

- **EMA pullback continuation:** fast EMA **8ŌĆō12**, slow EMA **18ŌĆō24**, RSI trigger **50ŌĆō55**, ATR stop multiple **0.8ŌĆō1.1**.
- **Bollinger range fade:** band deviation **1.8ŌĆō2.3**, RSI2 extreme **5ŌĆō10** and **90ŌĆō95**, ADX cap **16ŌĆō20**.
- **Donchian volatility breakout:** channel length **15ŌĆō30**, ADX floor **20ŌĆō28**, ATR expansion threshold **1.05ŌĆō1.25**.
- **MACD-Stochastic re-entry:** Stochastic trigger **20ŌĆō30**, ATR multiple **0.7ŌĆō0.95**, higher-timeframe trend MA around **150ŌĆō250**.

A practical Python/MT5 risk-sizing pattern looks like this:

```python
# illustrative Python sizing logic
risk_cash = equity * risk_pct
one_lot_loss = abs(mt5.order_calc_profit(
    mt5.ORDER_TYPE_BUY, symbol, 1.0, entry_price, stop_price
))
raw_volume = risk_cash / one_lot_loss
volume = floor_to_step(raw_volume, volume_step)
volume = min(max(volume, volume_min), volume_max)
```

That pattern is robust precisely because it respects the brokerŌĆÖs symbol settings instead of assuming a universal BTC contract model. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn29search0Ņłéturn29search3Ņłéturn21search2Ņłéturn28search2Ņłü

## Risk controls and deployment priorities

Because account size is unspecified, the most stable control variable is **risk as a percentage of equity**. I would keep the live per-trade risk inside the strategy bands above, cap total daily realised loss at about **1.5% to 2.0%**, and stop trading for the session after **three consecutive losses** or after a significant spread regime worsening. That discipline matters because the cost-aware Bitcoin evidence shows higher-frequency technical trading is precisely where performance becomes more vulnerable to small increases in transaction costs. On an MT5 netting account, that discipline should extend to portfolio structure as well: only one live BTC position per symbol, controlled centrally. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn26view0Ņłéturn32search0Ņłéturn21search1Ņłü

If I had to prioritise deployment, I would start with **EMA pullback continuation** and **Bollinger range fade** as the core pair, because together they cover both trend and range conditions with more manageable slippage. I would then add **Donchian volatility breakout** only in clear expansion regimes, and treat **MACD-Stochastic re-entry** as the secondary continuation model for choppier trends. The win-rate ranges in this report are engineering estimates, not broker-specific backtest results. Before live risk, they should be validated in MT5 Strategy Tester, then on forward periods, then on a demo or very small live allocation with full logging of fill quality, spread, and realised slippage by hour and by strategy. ŅłĆciteŅłéturn4search0Ņłéturn2search1Ņłéturn20search1Ņłéturn20search2Ņłéturn20search12Ņłü